The idea behind these ensemble gates is based on the following considerations: quantum information can be stored in the hyperfine sublevels of the ground state of alkali-metal atoms, denoted as  ${|{0}\rangle} $ and  ${|{1}\rangle} $. The ground state of a mesoscopic ensemble which consists of \textit{N} atoms is denoted as  ${|{\bar {0}}\rangle} =\frac{1}{\sqrt{N}}{|{00...0}\rangle} $. In the regime of Rydberg blockade we can use adiabatic passage to deterministically excite a collective state with a single Rydberg excitation  ${|{\bar {1} }\rangle} =\frac{1}{\sqrt{N}}\sum\limits_{j=1}^N{|{00...r_j...0}\rangle}$. This state can be then mapped onto the other hyperfine sublevel by a coherent single-atom  $\pi $ pulse. Therefore we consider the states ${|{\bar 0}\rangle} ={|{00...0}\rangle} $ and  ${|{\bar 1}\rangle} =\frac{1}{\sqrt{N}}\sum\limits_{j=1}^N {|{00...1_j...0}\rangle} $ as logical states of the ensemble qubit. We have to take into account the accumulation of the \textit{N}-dependent dynamic phase during the first adiabatic sequence, as shown in figure~\ref{Scheme}(f). If the adiabatic excitation of the ensemble into the Rydberg state is followed by coherent  $\pi $ pulse at   ${|{r}\rangle} \to {|{1}\rangle}$ transition, the final qubit state will be  ${|{1}\rangle}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{N}}e^{\mathit{i\alpha}_N}\sum\limits_{j=1}^N{|{00...1_j...0}\rangle}$ where  $\alpha_N$ is the accumulated phase, which depends on the number of atoms in the ensemble and parameters of laser excitation (Rabi frequencies and pulse shapes). Our simulations of quantum tomography (to be given below) confirm that this phase accumulation does not affect the gate performance, but this is true only in the case when switching the detuning from the intermediate level in the double STIRAP sequence is used.

